<h2 id="key-features">⚡ Key Features Compared</h2>

<h3>Omnichannel & POS Integration</h3>

Shopify Plus dominates here. Shopify POS Pro integrates natively, sharing inventory, customer data, and order history across online and in-store channels in real-time. The system handles complex scenarios like buy-online-pickup-in-store (BOPIS), endless aisle ordering from locations, and cross-location returns without custom development.

BigCommerce requires third-party POS solutions. While they partner with providers like Square and ConnectPOS, the integration depth doesn't match Shopify's native solution. Our team spent 40 additional hours configuring inventory sync for a BigCommerce client that worked out-of-box on Shopify.

For luxury operators running multiple boutiques, this difference alone often justifies Shopify Plus's premium pricing.

<h3>Clienteling & Customer Data</h3>

Luxury retail lives and dies on client relationships. Both platforms support customer segmentation and purchase history, but Shopify Plus's ecosystem includes purpose-built luxury clienteling tools.

Endear, the leading clienteling platform for luxury retail, offers deep Shopify Plus integration. Sales associates can access complete customer profiles including online browsing behavior, purchase history across all channels, and personalized recommendations. The same integration on BigCommerce requires custom API work.

Shopify Plus also offers Shopify Audiences, using aggregated merchant data to improve ad targeting. For luxury brands spending $50,000+ monthly on digital acquisition, the improved ROAS typically returns 3-5x the platform cost.

<h3>B2B & Wholesale Capabilities</h3>

BigCommerce Enterprise wins the B2B comparison decisively. Native features include:

- Customer-specific price lists without apps
- Quote management with approval workflows  
- Purchase order support and net payment terms
- Company account structures with buyer permissions
- Shared shopping lists for repeat wholesale orders

Shopify Plus launched B2B features in 2022, but they still require Shopify Plus B2B (additional cost) and lack the depth of BigCommerce's offering. For luxury brands where wholesale represents 40%+ of revenue, BigCommerce's B2B capabilities often tip the decision.

<h3>Checkout Customization</h3>

Shopify Plus offers Checkout Extensibility, replacing the legacy checkout.liquid with app-based customization. You can add custom fields, modify shipping options based on product type, and implement luxury-specific features like gift messaging and VIP expedited processing.

BigCommerce allows full checkout customization through their Stencil framework. The flexibility is greater, but the development burden shifts to your team. Most luxury brands don't need that level of customization—they need the specific customizations to work reliably.

Shopify Scripts, exclusive to Plus, enables automatic discounts and custom shipping rules. We've implemented VIP-tier pricing that automatically applies when recognized customers check out, exclusive early access for top clients, and region-specific pricing that adjusts automatically.

<h3>International & Multi-Currency</h3>

Both platforms support multi-currency, but implementation differs significantly.

Shopify Plus with Shopify Markets enables local currencies, payment methods, and duty/tax calculation across 200+ markets. The system automatically shows localized pricing and handles currency conversion at checkout. For luxury brands selling globally—which is most of them—this reduces cart abandonment by 15-25%.

BigCommerce supports multi-currency but requires more configuration. International selling works, but the out-of-box experience isn't as polished. Several implementations required custom work to match the Shopify Markets experience.

<div class="callout-blue">
<strong>Tip:</strong> For luxury brands, enable local payment methods in key markets. Alipay in China, iDEAL in Netherlands, Klarna in Sweden. Both platforms support these, but Shopify Markets makes activation simpler. We've seen 20%+ conversion improvements from adding local payment options.
</div>

